ðŸ”¹Create Users & Set Permissions
Create User
sudo useradd demouser          -- default primary group of demouser is demouser  

Create Group
sudo groupadd demogroup

To change primary group of user
sudo usermod -g demogroup demouser    --now primary group changed of demouser is demogroup

To add this user to secondary group sudo
sudo usermod -aG sudo devuser     

List all users

Users are listed in /etc/passwd.
cat /etc/passwd

Or, to see only usernames:
cut -d: -f1 /etc/passwd

# Check ownership of a file
ls -l file.txt  

# Change ownership
sudo chown devuser:devuser file.txt  

# Change permissions
chmod 600 file.txt    # Owner read/write only
chmod 755 script.sh   # Owner all, others read/execute

ðŸ”¹Write a Script to Monitor CPU Usage

Create cpu_monitor.sh:

#!/bin/bash
# Simple CPU usage monitor

THRESHOLD=80

usage=$(top -bn1 | grep "Cpu(s)" | awk '{print 100 - $8}')
usage=${usage%.*}   # remove decimals

echo "Current CPU usage: $usage%"

if [ "$usage" -gt "$THRESHOLD" ]; then
    echo "Warning: CPU usage is above $THRESHOLD%!"
fi


Make it executable:

chmod +x cpu_monitor.sh
./cpu_monitor.sh

ðŸ”¹Deploy a Service (Apache or Nginx)

Example with Nginx:

sudo apt update
sudo apt install nginx -y

# Start service
sudo systemctl start nginx

# Check status
systemctl status nginx

# Stop service
sudo systemctl stop nginx

Then, open browser â†’ http://<your-server-ip> â†’ you should see the Nginx welcome page ðŸŽ‰

